3a.¶

The first network (The one that I made from Gephi) represents every character portrayed on the HBO series Game of Thrones, based on the novels by George R. R. Martin. I color coded the characters based on their importance in the story telling. Warm colors such as red, orange and yellow represent major characters. Whereas, cool colors such as blue categorize minor characters. In addition to utilizing colors, I also distinguished major characters from minor characters based on the size of the “nodes”.

Each character's name is written on a circular node. For example, the character of Tyrion Lannister is a major character in the Game of Thrones series. In my visual network, I have written his name on a large, red node. In contrast, the character of Brynden Tully, who plays a minor role in the series, is shown as a small, blue node.

The relationship between the character’s interactions are denoted as edges or lines connecting the nodes. Just as size and color coding denoted the importance of individual characters, the same can be true for the interactions between them. Every time a character interacts with another, a line is drawn between their nodes. The more interaction or stronger a relationship between two characters, the thicker and warmer color the line between them becomes. However, if two characters have minimal interaction or a weak relationship, the line between them is thinner and cooler in color. This can be exemplified by the thick, orange line between Tyrion Lannier and Sansa Stark, who are married in the series.

Note to Game of Thrones fans: Despite the strong connection between Daenerys Targaryen and Jon Snow in the series, there is no edge/line between them depicted in the network visualization. This is due to the CVS file which did not connect the lovers in the data.

Another way to describe color is with a node’s degree. Degree is the number of interactions a single character has made with other characters in the series. Higher degree value means a warmer color (such as red), while lower degree value is shown as a cool color (such as blue).

Furthermore, a node’s size is directly linked to its eigenvector centrality. Higher eigenvector centrality values are denoted with a larger node size and vice versa.

3b.¶

The graph of my second visualization also represents characters in the Game of Thrones series. Each node denotes a specific character. While all of the nodes are blue, the different shades (of blue) distinguish major characters from minor characters. The darker and more saturated blue colored nodes depict more important/major characters, while the lighter and less saturated blue colored nodes represent lesser/minor characters. Once again, a node’s color is directly based on its degree centrality. Higher degree centrality values mean a darker, more saturated shade of blue, while lower degree centrality values are shown as lighter, less saturated hues of blue. In addition to color, the size of each node also contributes to the importance of a character. Bigger nodes symbolize major characters, and vice versa. Once more, the size of each node is based on its eigenvector centrality value. Major characters have larger eigenvector centrality values; whereas minor characters have lower eigenvector centrality values.

Much like the first visualization, relationships/interactions between the characters are represented as lines/edges linking nodes together. However, unlike the first visualization, all of the edges have the exact same properties (including thickness and color).

Unfortunately, it is impossible to determine which character corresponds to which node. This is because nx_altair does not permit the user to label nodes.

The histogram in my second visualization represents the number of characters who have a specific value of degree centrality. The x-axis displays each possible value of a node’s degree centrality. Whereas the y-axis represents the number of characters that have a particular degree centrality value.

Major characters can be found between the center and the right end of the histogram, ranging from the values of 0.15 - 0.33. (Interestingly, Tyrion Lannister has the highest value at 0.33) Minor characters are located to the left end of the histogram, ranging from the values of 0.00 - 0.15. (Unsurprisingly, a large majority of the characters in this visualization can be found here as minor characters.)
